    <h3 style="margin-top:-10px"><em>RaspianOS Installation und Konfiguration</em> </h3>
    <hr>
  </div>


  <p><i><b>schedule+</b></i> App must run on a RPI with a Raspbian operating system stored on a SDcard.
    <br>
    To install the operating system on an SD card, you can use the <b>Raspberry Pi Imager</b>, which must be installed on a desktop with an SD card reader.
    <br> The Raspberry Pi Imager can be downloaded from
    <a class="moz-txt-link-freetext" href="https://www.raspberrypi.com/software/">https://www.raspberrypi.com/software/</a>
  </p>

  <h4>OS Installation on a SDcard</h4>

  <div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <img alt="Imager1" src="pict/Imager_1.png" width="400"></div>

  <p>Insert the SDcard (e.g with 16 GB capacity, recommanded: use fat32 formatting) into an SDcardReader on your desktop and start.<br>

    With the Imager select an OS like "Raspberry PI OS (32-bit) 0.8 GB / Bullseye" or
    "Raspberry PI OS Lite (32-bit) / Bullseye no desktop 0.3 GB <br>
  </p>
  <div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <img alt="Imager3" src="pict/Imager_3.png" width="366"></div>

  <p>and the storage device (shows a 16 GB with some 'old' installation,
    which will be overwritten)<br>
  </p>
  <div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <img alt="Imager2" src="pict/Imager_2.png" width="400"></div>

  <p>Before writing to the Storage Device, take a look at the <b>Advanced Options</b> that are available with the cogwheel
  </p>
  <div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <img alt="Imager4" src="pict/Imager_4.png" width="427"></div>

  <p>Set the following :</p>
  <p>-- hostname (default 'pi')<br>
    -- enable SSH with 'Use password authentication'<br>
    -- set user name and PW<br>
    -- optional WLAN parameters<br>
    -- set locale settings (Timezone, keyboard)<br>
    -- eject media when finished<br>
  </p>
  <p>Press <b>[Save]</b> and <b>[Write]</b></p>
  <p>Stay tuned .. writing and reviewing the 0.3 GB Lite version took about 6 minutes and is finally finished with:
    <br>
  </p>
  <div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <img alt="Imager5" src="pict/Imager_5.png" width="430"></div>

  <p>Remove SDcard, install it into the RPI and power it on.</p>

  <h4>Set fixed IP for the RPI via Router menu</h4>

  <p>Open the router network overview and find the RPI with the
    'hostname' defined before.<br>
    Configure the 'Name' and set a 'fixed' IP.<br>
    These changes need a reboot of the RPI to activate them.<br>

    After the RPI has been restarted, the RPI settings should be checked again on the router.</p>

  <h4>Access the RPI using SSH</h4>
  <p>On the desktop console, type <code>ssh &lt;username&gt;@&lt;fixed RPI ip&gt;</code>. <br>
    You will see a response according to this:
  </p>
  <pre style="margin-left: 15px; margin-right:15px">
        xuser@xuser-xfce:~$ ssh <a
            class="moz-txt-link-abbreviated moz-txt-link-freetext"
            href="mailto:pi@192.0.2.75">pi@192.0.2.75</a>
        @@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@
        @   WARNING: REMOTE HOST IDENTIFICATION HAS
          CHANGED!   @
        @@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@
        IT IS POSSIBLE THAT SOMEONE IS DOING SOMETHING
          NASTY!
        Someone could be eavesdropping on you right now
          (man-in-the-middle attack)!
        It is also possible that a host key has just
          been changed.
        The fingerprint for the ECDSA key sent by the
          remote host is
        SHA256:OzDb8....................ql6+MuAO7mY.
        Please contact your system administrator.
        Add correct host key in
          /home/xuser/.ssh/known_hosts to get rid of this message.
        Offending ECDSA key in
          /home/xuser/.ssh/known_hosts:2
          remove with:
          ssh-keygen -f "/home/xuser/.ssh/known_hosts"
          -R "192.0.2.75"
        ECDSA host key for 192.0.2.75 has changed and
          you have requested strict checking.
        Host key verification failed.
        xuser@xuser-xfce:~$
        xuser@xuser-xfce:~$ ssh-keygen -f
          "/home/xuser/.ssh/known_hosts" -R "192.0.2.75"</pre>


  <p>The next login to the console with <code> ssh pi@192.0.2.75 </code> will cause the user login to also request the PW (see above).</p>

  <p id="update" style="margin-left: 25px;"><b><i> IMPORTANT</i></b> The installed OS needs an 'Update' and 'Upgrade' to work correctly!<br>
    Use: <code> sudo apt-get update </code><br>
    and: <code> sudo apt-get upgrade </code>
  </p>

  <p>The RPI is ready to install and run <i><b>schedule+</b></i><br>
  </p>

